{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLM judges inherit the biases of their training: they were trained to predict text that humans wrote, and humans have systematic preferences for certain response styles (longer, formatted, authoritative) that don't always correlate with factual accuracy or genuine helpfulness. Bias mitigation is not optional \u2014 without it, LLM-as-judge pipelines measure training-data aesthetics rather than response quality."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "LLM Judge Bias Taxonomy: 7 bias types with effect sizes and mitigation strategies \u2014 position, verbosity, self-preference, sycophancy, format, recency, familiarity/authority"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Position Bias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When two responses are presented in positions A and B, the judge disproportionately selects A as the winner. Effect size: 5\u201315 percentage points above chance. This bias holds even when the judge is explicitly instructed to ignore order."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Detection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def measure_position_bias(\n    judge_fn,\n    question_response_pairs: list[tuple[str, str, str]],\n    # list of (question, resp_a, resp_b) where resp_a is the true better response\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Swaps A/B and measures how often the judge changes its verdict.\n    True position-bias-free judge: flip_rate = 0 (consistent verdicts).\n    A judge with position bias: frequently changes verdict when order swaps.\n    \"\"\"\n    consistent = position_favored = 0\n    for q, r_a, r_b in question_response_pairs:\n        order1 = judge_fn(q, r_a, r_b)  # 'A', 'B', 'tie'\n        order2 = judge_fn(q, r_b, r_a)  # A/B labels now swapped\n        flip = {'A': 'B', 'B': 'A', 'tie': 'tie'}[order2]\n        if order1 == flip:\n            consistent += 1\n        else:\n            position_favored += 1\n    n = len(question_response_pairs)\n    return {\n        'consistency_rate': consistent / n,\n        'position_bias_rate': position_favored / n,\n    }"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mitigation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Run each comparison in both orders. When the judge's verdict flips with the presentation order, call it a tie (the judge cannot distinguish the responses reliably). This halves the throughput but eliminates position-driven errors:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def pairwise_debiased(judge_fn, q: str, r1: str, r2: str) -> str:\n    v1 = judge_fn(q, r1, r2)   # 'A'->r1 wins, 'B'->r2 wins\n    v2 = judge_fn(q, r2, r1)   # 'A'->r2 wins, 'B'->r1 wins\n    # Translate v2 into r1/r2 terms\n    flip = {'A': 'r2', 'B': 'r1', 'tie': 'tie'}\n    abs1 = {'A': 'r1', 'B': 'r2', 'tie': 'tie'}[v1]\n    abs2 = flip[v2]\n    return abs1 if abs1 == abs2 else 'tie'"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Verbosity Bias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Longer responses are rated higher even when the additional length consists of filler, caveats, and repetition. Effect size: 3\u20138pp. This bias comes from training data patterns: human raters on crowdwork platforms tend to prefer longer responses because they feel more thorough."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Detection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def measure_verbosity_bias(\n    judge_fn,\n    prompts: list[str],\n    short_responses: list[str],\n    long_responses: list[str],\n    # long responses = short + padding; same factual content\n) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Returns fraction of times longer response is preferred.\"\"\"\n    long_wins = 0\n    for q, short, long in zip(prompts, short_responses, long_responses):\n        verdict = judge_fn(q, long, short)  # long is A, short is B\n        if verdict == 'A':  # long wins\n            long_wins += 1\n    return long_wins / len(prompts)\n    # Random baseline = 0.5; verbosity-biased judge >> 0.5"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mitigation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Add an explicit anti-verbosity instruction to the judge system prompt. AlpacaEval 2.0 uses Length-Controlled (LC) win rate, which down-weights comparisons where the preferred response is substantially longer:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "VERBOSITY_AWARE_SYSTEM = '''You are an expert evaluator.\nEvaluate response quality, NOT length. A concise, accurate response\nis better than a lengthy but padded one.\nIf a response adds caveats, restates the question, or includes unnecessary\nsections that add no information value, penalise it \u2014 do not reward length.\nOutput: {\"winner\": \"A\"|\"B\"|\"tie\", \"reason\": \"<one sentence>\"}'''\n\n# LC win rate (AlpacaEval 2.0 approach)\ndef lc_win_rate(\n    results: list[dict],  # [{winner, len_a, len_b}, ...]\n    base_length_ratio: float = 1.0,\n) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Length-controlled win rate: downweights pairs where winner is much longer.\"\"\"\n    weights = []\n    for r in results:\n        # weight inversely proportional to length ratio of winning response\n        if r['winner'] == 'A':\n            ratio = r['len_a'] / max(r['len_b'], 1)\n        elif r['winner'] == 'B':\n            ratio = r['len_b'] / max(r['len_a'], 1)\n        else:\n            ratio = 1.0\n        weight = 1.0 / max(ratio / base_length_ratio, 1.0)\n        weights.append((r['winner'] in ('A', 'tie'), weight))\n    total_w = sum(w for _, w in weights)\n    a_w = sum(w for won, w in weights if won)\n    return a_w / total_w if total_w > 0 else 0.0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Self-Preference Bias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An LLM judge rates responses that resemble its own generation style higher than responses of equal quality from a different model family. Effect size: 10\u201315pp. GPT-4 preferring GPT-4 outputs over equally good Claude outputs is not a capability difference \u2014 it is a stylistic preference baked in through training."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Detection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def measure_self_preference(\n    judge_fn,       # the judge model (e.g., gpt-4)\n    alt_judge_fn,   # a different model family as judge (e.g., claude-3-5-sonnet)\n    questions: list[str],\n    responses_same_family: list[str],   # generated by same family as judge\n    responses_other_family: list[str],  # generated by different family\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Compare win rate for same-family vs other-family responses.\"\"\"\n    judge_prefers_same = judge_prefers_other = 0\n    alt_prefers_same = alt_prefers_other = 0\n    for q, r_same, r_other in zip(questions, responses_same_family, responses_other_family):\n        j = judge_fn(q, r_same, r_other)\n        if j == 'A': judge_prefers_same += 1\n        elif j == 'B': judge_prefers_other += 1\n        a = alt_judge_fn(q, r_same, r_other)\n        if a == 'A': alt_prefers_same += 1\n        elif a == 'B': alt_prefers_other += 1\n    n = len(questions)\n    return {\n        'judge_same_win_rate':  judge_prefers_same / n,\n        'altjudge_same_win_rate': alt_prefers_same / n,\n        'self_preference_delta': (judge_prefers_same - alt_prefers_same) / n,\n    }"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mitigation: Multi-Judge Panel"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Use judges from different model families and aggregate their verdicts. Self-preference biases in opposite directions across families cancel out in the aggregate:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def panel_judge(\n    judges: list,  # list of judge callables from different families\n    question: str,\n    resp_a: str,\n    resp_b: str,\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Majority vote across judges from different families.\"\"\"\n    votes = {'A': 0, 'B': 0, 'tie': 0}\n    for judge in judges:\n        verdict = judge(question, resp_a, resp_b)\n        votes[verdict] += 1\n    winner = max(votes, key=votes.__getitem__)\n    # If no majority (e.g., A/B/tie with 3 judges), call tie\n    if votes[winner] == 1 and len(judges) >= 3:\n        return 'tie'\n    return winner"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sycophancy and Authority Bias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A judge shown a human assessment before seeing the responses will tend to agree with it \u2014 even if its independent assessment would differ. This is sycophancy: the judge defers to perceived authority rather than forming an independent judgment."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Related: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "authority bias",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " appears when responses are labeled with model names. A response labeled \"GPT-4\" is rated higher than an identical response labeled \"GPT-2\", even when the content is identical:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Experiment demonstrating authority bias\n# Identical text, different label\nresponse_text = 'The mitochondria is the powerhouse of the cell.'\n\n# These two prompts produce different scores from a biased judge:\nprompt_with_label_high = f'[Response from GPT-4o]\\n{response_text}'\nprompt_with_label_low  = f'[Response from GPT-2]\\n{response_text}'\n\n# Mitigation: always anonymize model names in judge prompts\ndef anonymize_prompt(response: str, label: str = 'Response') -> str:\n    return f'[{label}]\\n{response}'\n\n# In pairwise: use [Response A] / [Response B] only \u2014 never model names"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mitigation: Blind Judging"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Never expose model names, organization names, or stylistic hints about authorship to the judge. Anonymize all responses to generic labels ([Response A], [Response B]) and strip any headers or footers that identify the source:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import re\n\nMODEL_IDENTIFIERS = [\n    'GPT-4', 'GPT-3.5', 'Claude', 'Gemini', 'Llama', 'Mistral',\n    'ChatGPT', 'Bard', 'Copilot', 'Anthropic', 'OpenAI', 'Google',\n]\n\ndef blind_response(text: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Remove model-identifying strings from a response.\"\"\"\n    cleaned = text\n    for identifier in MODEL_IDENTIFIERS:\n        # Replace with generic 'the model'\n        cleaned = re.sub(identifier, 'the model', cleaned, flags=re.IGNORECASE)\n    return cleaned"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Format Bias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Judges prefer responses that use markdown formatting (headers, bullet points, code blocks) over plain prose, even when the content is identical. Effect size: 2\u20135pp. The bias stems from training data: high-quality human responses on platforms like Stack Overflow and GitHub tend to use markdown, so the model learned to associate formatting with quality."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mitigation: explicitly instruct the judge to ignore formatting:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "FORMAT_NEUTRAL_INSTRUCTION = '''\nIMPORTANT: Evaluate CONTENT quality only \u2014 ignore formatting.\nA response in plain prose is not worse than one with headers and bullets\nif the information content is equivalent.\nMarkdown formatting does NOT indicate higher quality.\n'''\n\n# Add this to your judge system prompt before the rubric"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Measuring Overall Judge Bias: The Consistency Audit"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A consistency audit systematically measures all major biases in a single evaluation pass. Run it on a held-out set of test pairs where you have ground-truth human labels:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass\nclass JudgeBiasAudit:\n    position_bias_rate: float      # fraction of verdicts changed by swap\n    verbosity_bias_rate: float     # fraction preferring longer response\n    human_agreement_rate: float    # fraction matching human labels\n    self_pref_delta: float         # extra win rate for same-family responses\n\n    def report(self) -> str:\n        flags = []\n        if self.position_bias_rate > 0.15:\n            flags.append(f'HIGH position bias ({self.position_bias_rate:.0%})')\n        if self.verbosity_bias_rate > 0.60:\n            flags.append(f'HIGH verbosity bias ({self.verbosity_bias_rate:.0%})')\n        if self.human_agreement_rate < 0.65:\n            flags.append(f'LOW human agreement ({self.human_agreement_rate:.0%})')\n        if self.self_pref_delta > 0.10:\n            flags.append(f'HIGH self-preference delta ({self.self_pref_delta:.0%})')\n        status = 'PASS' if not flags else 'FAIL'\n        return f'Judge audit: {status}\\n' + '\\n'.join(f'  ! {f}' for f in flags)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
